{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:04:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1937"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1937"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.23,0.01,0.47,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53976"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1937"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1937"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39447"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1444"},{"type":"tags","id":"2309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8305"},{"type":"tags","id":"8386"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44941"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53976"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a several-week history of right ear discharge. He reports having ear pain prior to the onset of discharge. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 84/min and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. There are scars of a healing scabies infestation over the forearms. Otoscopic examination of the right ear reveals purulent discharge in the ear canal. Rinne\u0027s test shows bone conduction greater than air conduction on the right. Weber\u0027s test lateralises to the right. Otoscopy reveals the following (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aminoglycoside-containing ear drops (dexamethasone + framycetin + gramicidin)","Amoxicillin and clavulanic acid oral tablets","Fluconazole oral tablets","Ciprofloxacin ear drops","Ciprofloxacin oral tablets"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with chronic suppurative otitis media (CSOM), characterized by persistent ear discharge, conductive hearing loss, and a perforated tympanic membrane visible on otoscopy. The most appropriate treatment in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eciprofloxacin ear drops\u003C/strong\u003E. Ciprofloxacin is a broad-spectrum antibiotic that effectively covers common pathogens in CSOM, including \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. Topical administration allows for high local concentrations with minimal systemic absorption, making it both effective and safe for use in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAminoglycoside-containing ear drops\u003C/strong\u003E (such as those containing dexamethasone, framycetin, and gramicidin) should be avoided in cases of tympanic membrane perforation due to the risk of ototoxicity. Aminoglycosides can potentially cause irreversible cochlear and vestibular damage when they enter the middle ear through a perforated tympanic membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin and clavulanic acid oral tablets\u003C/strong\u003E are not the first-line treatment for uncomplicated CSOM. Oral antibiotics are generally reserved for cases where the infection has spread beyond the middle ear, or in patients with uncontrolled diabetes or immunosuppression. In most cases, topical antibiotics alone are sufficient and preferable to oral antibiotics, as they reduce the risk of systemic side effects and antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFluconazole oral tablets\u003C/strong\u003E are antifungal medications and are not indicated for bacterial CSOM. Fungal otitis externa is a different condition and would present with different clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin oral tablets\u003C/strong\u003E, while containing the same active ingredient as the ear drops, are not the preferred route of administration for uncomplicated CSOM. Topical treatment allows for higher local concentrations of the antibiotic with less systemic exposure, making it more effective and safer, especially in pediatric patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antibiotic treatment, management of CSOM should include careful cleaning and drying of the ear, avoidance of water entry into the ear, and follow-up to ensure resolution of the infection and to assess for any complications or need for surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ciprofloxacin ear drops are the first-line treatment for chronic suppurative otitis media due to their broad-spectrum coverage and safety profile.","Aminoglycoside-containing ear drops should be avoided in cases of tympanic membrane perforation due to their ototoxicity.","Oral antibiotics are generally not indicated for uncomplicated chronic suppurative otitis media unless there is evidence of spread beyond the middle ear."],"references":["Phillips JS, Yung MW, Burton MJ, Swan IRC. Evidence review and ENT-UK consensus report for the use of aminoglycoside-containing ear drops in the presence of an open middle ear. Clin Otolaryngol 2007;32:330-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17883551/","Rosenfeld RM, Singer M, Wasserman JM, Stinnett SS. Systematic review of topical antimicrobial therapy for acute otitis externa. Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2006;134(4 suppl):S24\u2013S48. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16638474/","Ohyama M, Furuta S, Ueno K, Katsuda K, Nobori T, Kiyota R, et al. Ofloxacin Otic Solution in Patients With Otitis Media: An Analysis of Drug Concentrations. Archives of Otolaryngology\u2013Head \u0026 Neck Surgery. 1999 Mar 1;125(3):337\u201340. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10190808/","Onali MA, Bareeqa SB, Zia S, Ahmed SI, Owais A, Ahmad AN. Efficacy of Empirical Therapy With Combined Ciprofloxacin Versus Topical Drops Alone in Patients With Tubotympanic Chronic Suppurative Otitis Media: A Randomized Double-Blind Controlled Trial. Clinical Medicine Insights: Ear, Nose and Throat. 2018 Jan 11;11:1179550617751907. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29348711/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39447"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1937"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18430"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18430"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/935e86d5-c773-42c6-acbd-ba2864c386d7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/935e86d5-c773-42c6-acbd-ba2864c386d7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":720,"height":